      <hedline>
        <hl1>Stevenson's Reading</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Beschloss letter on his account of Adlai Stevenson's reading habits; quotes Stevenson himself saying in early 1960's that he had not read a book in five years; suggests admiring leaders as they really are (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Adlai Stevenson's longtime associate William McC. Blair Jr. (letter, June 16) contests my suggestion (Op-Ed, June 11) that ''months or years'' could pass before Stevenson read a book. But Stevenson's official biography by John Bartlow Martin quotes Stevenson himself (as recounted by his colleague Philip Klutznick) privately saying in the early 1960's, ''I haven't read a book in five years.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Adlai Stevenson's longtime associate William McC. Blair Jr. (letter, June 16) contests my suggestion (Op-Ed, June 11) that ''months or years'' could pass before Stevenson read a book. But Stevenson's official biography by John Bartlow Martin quotes Stevenson himself (as recounted by his colleague Philip Klutznick) privately saying in the early 1960's, ''I haven't read a book in five years.''</p>
        <p>Especially as a native Illinoisan, I bow to no one in admiring Adlai Stevenson's leadership qualities.  But why not admire our leaders as they really were?</p>
        <p>MICHAEL BESCHLOSS  Washington, June 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
